def bokeh_rgb_image(rgb, fig):
    #rgb = x,y,rgb
    
    rgb = np.flipud(rgb)
    img = np.empty((rgb.shape[0],rgb.shape[1]), dtype=np.uint32)
    N = img
    view = img.view(dtype=np.uint8).reshape((img.shape[0], img.shape[1], 4))

    view[:, :, 0] = rgb[:, :, 0]
    view[:, :, 1] = rgb[:, :, 1]
    view[:, :, 2] = rgb[:, :, 2]
    view[:, :, 3] = 255

    fig.image_rgba(image=[img], x=0, y=0, dw=rgb.shape[0], dh=rgb.shape[1])
    #p.line(x=[100, 500], y=[100,500])

    #output_file("image_rgba.html", title="image_rgba.py example")
    fig.axis.visible = False

def bokeh_bw_image(bw, fig, pallette = 'Greys256', show_axis = False):
    #bw = 2 dimensional shaped image
    #fig = handle for image
    #palette="Magma256"
    
    #bw = np.rollaxis(bw, 1, 0)
    bw = np.flipud(bw)
    #print(bw.shape)
    fig.x_range.range_padding = fig.y_range.range_padding = 0
    fig.image(image=[bw], x=0, y=0, dw=bw.shape[1], dh = bw.shape[0], palette=pallette)
    fig.axis.visible = show_axis
    fig.x_range = Range1d(0, bw.shape[1])
    fig.y_range = Range1d(0, bw.shape[0])
    
color_generator = itertools.cycle(palette)

def load_matlab_file(file):
    mat = loadmat(file)
    data_dict = {name : mat['sensor'][0][0][i].flatten() for i, name in enumerate(mat['sensor'].dtype.names)}
    return data_dict
In [7]:
def getTifffilesMetadata(file):
    #file = path to tif image file
    #return dictionary{each image metata data dictionary{tag}}
    with tifffile.TiffFile(file) as tif:
        imgs = {}
        for i, page in enumerate(tif):
            t={}
            for ctag in page.tags.values():
                if isinstance(ctag.value, int):
                    
                    t[ctag.name] = ctag.value
                elif isinstance(ctag.value, tuple):
                    
                    t[ctag.name] = ctag.value
                else:
                    string1= ctag.value.decode('utf-8')
                    for line in  string1.split('\n'):
                        index = line.find('=')
                        if index > 0:
                            cname = line[:index-1]
                            t[cname] = line[index+2:]
                    tagname = str
            imgs[i] =t
    return imgs

In [24]:
all_signal = []
for row, dseries in roi_list_df.iterrows():
    signal = np.zeros([timeseries.shape[0]], dtype = np.float)
    for layer in range(timeseries.shape[0]):
        cimage = timeseries[layer].flatten()
        signal[layer] = np.mean(cimage[dseries['roi_index']])
    all_signal.append(signal)
roi_list_df['signal'] = all_signal
signal_Back = []
#remove background
for row,dseries in roi_list_df.iterrows():
    signal_Back.append(dseries['signal'].astype(np.float) - roi_list_df['signal'].loc['background'].astype(np.float))
roi_list_df['signal-background'] = signal_Back

In [30]:
#create a pandas dataframe lining up the imaging and sensor data
def find_nearest(array, value):
    array = np.asarray(array)
    idx = (np.abs(array - value)).argmin()
    return idx
In [31]:
#downsampling sensor data to match imaging data
aligned_sensor = {}
for ct in timeEnd:
    aligned_sensor[ct] = {}
    indx = find_nearest(mat_dict2['time'], ct)
    for ckey in mat_dict2:
        aligned_sensor[ct][ckey] = mat_dict2[ckey][indx]
data_frame = pd.DataFrame(aligned_sensor).T
data_frame['roi'] = roi_list_df['signal-background'].loc[0]

legend_it =[]
#plot showing voltage
volt_array = data_frame[voltage_axis].values
p.extra_y_ranges = {"foo": Range1d(start=np.min(volt_array)-np.abs(np.min(volt_array)*0.8), end=np.max(volt_array))}
p.add_layout(LinearAxis(y_range_name='foo', axis_label = 'Volt (V)'), 'right')
for col in voltage_axis:
    c= p.line(x = data_frame.index, y=data_frame[col], y_range_name = 'foo', line_color =color_dict[col], line_alpha=0.8, line_width =2)
    legend_it.append((col, [c]))

for col in intensity_axis:
    c = p.line(x = data_frame.index,  y = data_frame['roi'], line_color = color_dict[col])
    legend_it.append((col, [c]))

legend.click_policy="hide"
p.add_layout(legend, 'right')
show(p)

ROI intensity is the change in intensity from the image over time and is plotted against the left y-axis The sensors are plotted against the right y-axis.
Two different sensors are measuing odor delivery:
MICS5524 == MiCEbay
PID
Valve5 is the valve that closes the default airyway when odor is being applied.
